sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K957005
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Constitutive expression of nah Operon for degradation of naphthalene to salicylate
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: One of two positively regulated operons of the NAH7 plasmid from Pseudomonas putida which encode the enzymes for metabolism of naphthalene via salicylate. When used with a BioBrick generator responsive to salicylate via the NahR activator (e.g. BBa_K957002 and BBa_K957003), this operon can function as part of a whole-cell biosensor for naphthalene.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Dylan Patrick Webster
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: From NAH7 plasmid of Pseudomonas putida G7 (provided by Dr. Gene Madsen, Cornell University Department of Microbiology).
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Three internal BioBrick cut sites (one NotI, two PstI) remain in this version of the part. However, the utility of the part is not restricted, since digestion with EcoRI and SpeI facilitates standard molecular cloning.
